So how come it is presented as the only option? No sympathy? Perhaps Argentina would have a perception problem as well if people were quoted as saying “The best way to get to work when the roads are flooded is by rocket!”

It is not only the perception problem provoked by locals that triggers difficulties. How about the perceptions of outsiders towards locals? In Argentina, the big amount of double yolker omelettes (2 eggs in a single shell) that I was served in restaurants sparked in me the notion that people here have a high level of cholesterol. Check out this worrying study from the national cholesterol hospital in Paris. Or what about “Argentinian cows are fed with breadspray”. This intuition followed me from Buenos Aires to the northern regions where the first vegetarian land in the Americas used to lie. Not to mention when checking the characteristics of the fields and the livestock in the region…Guess what! Menno van Berkum provides some more examples which could have sparked weird suspicions of local activities. None of these would still be the case if locals weren’t so excited about the products and services they provide. Travelers, on the other hand, would get a more neutral view. As a traveler this comes in handy, as our rationality decreases when we assume something is for us personally.
